Foot and mouth disease outbreaks in northern Uganda
-----------------------------------------------------
The Ugandan ministry of agriculture, animal husbandry and fisheries has
announced an outbreak of foot and mouth disease [FMD] in Unyama and Pakwelo
parishes in Gulu district, northern part of the east African country,
according to a report from Radio Uganda on Thursday [28 Jul 2005].
A statement issued by the commissioner of livestock, Dr. N. Kauta, was
quoted as saying that following the outbreak of FMD in the district,
quarantine restrictions are imposed on Bungatira and Paicho sub-counties of
the district immediately.
"Movement of livestock, livestock products and by-products from, to and
within Bungatira and Paicho sub-counties, in Gulu district is prohibited
with immediate effect until further notice," the statement said.
It said that all livestock markets in Bungatira and Paicho sub-counties
have also been closed with immediate effect.
"The veterinary staff, local councils, chiefs, enforcement personnel and
general public are required to enforce quarantine restrictions so that the
disease is brought under control," it added.
